{{For|the cricketer|Anton Roux}} {{Infobox artist | name = Antoine Roux | image = Jean-Baptiste de Havre-A.Roux mg 6205.jpg | caption = Antoine Roux, ''Jean-Baptiste du Havre in Marseille harbour'', watercolor, Marseille Naval Museum | birth_name = Ange-Joseph Antoine Roux | birth_date = 1765 | birth_place = [[Marseille]], [[France]] | death_date = {{death year and age|1835|1765}} | death_place = Marseille, France | nationality = France | field = Painting, drawing | movement = [[Marine art]] }} '''Ange-Joseph Antoine Roux''', "'''Antoine Roux'''" (1765–1835) was a French fine art [[Painting|painter]] who specialised in [[sea|maritime]] painting, sometimes referred to as [[marine art]].
== Career == Roux came from a [[Roux family (marine painters)|family of artists]] and primarily worked in [[Marseille]]. Early in life he was apprenticed to his father, [[Roux family (marine painters)|Joseph Roux]] (1752–93), an [[hydrography|hydrographer]] as well as an artist in his own right, spending his leisure hours painting and drawing.<ref name="pem">[http://www.pem.org/sites/roux/sketchbooks-100.html The Sketchbooks of Antoine Roux], Peabody Essex Museum, 2006.</ref><ref name="NMM">''[http://www.nmm.ac.uk/collections/explore/object.cfm?ID=PAG9744&picture=1#content French galley at Marseilles (PAG9744)] {{dead link|date=January 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}'', National Maritime Museum, Greenwich, London.</ref> He died of cholera in Marseille in 1835.<ref name=Meissonnier10 />
All Antoine's four children followed in his artistic footsteps, with his three sons becoming known for their painting as well: Mathieu-Antoine Roux (1799-1872); François Joseph Frédéric Roux (1805–1870), 'Frédéric', was apprenticed to [[Horace Vernet]]; and the third, François Geoffroy Roux (1811–1882), 'François', was appointed in 1876 as an official [[Peintre de la Marine]].<ref name="pem" /><ref name=Meissonnier10>Meissonnier, p.10</ref><ref name="Cordingly">Cordingly, David, Ships and Seascapes: An Introduction to Maritime Prints, Drawings and Watercolours, Philip Wilson, 2003, p. 155. {{ISBN|978-0-85667-484-6}}.</ref>
==Museum collections== *The [[Peabody Essex Museum]] in [[Salem, Massachusetts]] holds a collection of Roux's works. *The [[National Maritime Museum]], (NMM), [[London, England]]. *New York Public Library, ''USS President''.<ref name="Toll">Toll, Ian W., Six Frigates: The Epic History of the Founding of the U.S. Navy, Frontispiece, 2006. {{ISBN|978-0-393-33032-8}}.</ref> *The [[Mariners' Museum]] in [[Newport News, Virginia]] *[[Musée National de la Marine]] in [[Paris]], [[France]]
