{{short description|Part of a dramatic work such as a serial television or radio drama}}
{{Other uses}}

An '''episode''' is a coherent narrative unit within a larger [[drama]]tic work, such as a radio or television [[serial (radio and television)|series]]. The word derives from the Greek term ({{lang-grc|ἐπεισόδιον}})  (''epeisodion''), meaning the material contained between two songs or [[ode]]s in a Greek [[tragedy]].

== Description ==
An episode is a coherent narrative unit within a larger [[drama]]tic work. It is frequently used to describe units of television or radio [[serial (radio and television)|series]]. An episode is to a sequence as a [[Chapter (books)|chapter]] is to a [[book]]. Modern series episodes typically last 20 to 40 minutes in length.

== Etymology ==
The word derives from the Greek term ({{lang-grc|ἐπεισόδιον}})  (''epeisodion''), meaning the material contained between two songs or [[ode]]s in a Greek [[tragedy]].<ref>{{cite web |title=episode (n.) |url=https://www.etymonline.com/word/episode |website=Online Etymoloy Dictionary |accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref>

Episode is abbreviated as [[wikt:ep|ep]] (''plural'' eps).

